social_posts.post_text: The biggest impacts are made when we meet people eye to eye. Sometimes it requires getting down on a knee. Thanks @papastank for capturing this beautiful photo of Ruby at the end of her dance performance.

RUFA is looking for a Program Director!

Running Up For Air (RUFA) @runningupforair started back in the winter of 2011/2012 when laps on Grandeur Peak forced us to viscerally experience the air pollution that the Salt Lake Valley residents are frequently exposed to. The early days involved a handful of hearty friends willing to work together, breaking trail in brutal conditions, all to raise money for groups who work tirelessly for all of us. We liked the difficulty, were inspired to trailblaze, and it felt great converting our personal energy into something positive for humanity. It became a yearly ritual, eventually turned into a formal race, and then expanded to other sites across the U.S. and recently to Europe. 

I am so happy to announce that thanks to support from one of our key sponsors, RUFA is embarking on its next chapter, which begins with hiring a Program Director. The Program Director will work in close coordination with our team of volunteer race directors to ensure events are properly resourced and consistently organized, and that our runners and nonprofit partners receive relevant and timely information throughout the year.

We’re looking for someone who is dynamic, detail-oriented, and passionate about our cause. The Program Director will be responsible for maintaining RUFA’s annual cadence of events and deadlines, both internally and externally, through consistent communication and planning. The Program Director is proactive, highly organized, and has a deep understanding of the running community and trail running race operations…

Applications will be accepted through January 23rd! We would love for you to pass this on and share with friends who you think might be a good fit. See link in bio.

Join me TONIGHT for our 2023 RUFA pre-race air quality discussion at the @patagoniaslc store. We have arranged a great panel. It will also be streamed live via YouTube. See link in bio for details and to RSVP.
My mother (right) is ready for @runningupforair, how about you?

Dr. Kerry Kelly (Chemical engineering faculty at the University of Utah) has set up two air quality sensors at the Church Fork aid station so we can monitor real time. You can see the sensor at the link in our bio or via the up for air website.

The people of RUFA are what make it so special.  What an incredible community and experience we have built over the years. 2023 is proving to be a major success by all measures.

Follow along on the @runningupforair account to catch all the action.
Phoebe on the final push to the summit of Grandeur at @runningupforair!! Special girl, incredible mom!
Phoebe  on the summit of lap 2! @runningupforair

I am so proud of Phoebe and Mindy. They teamed up for two laps on Grandeur Peak @runningupforair and in the process contributed to an incredible wave of positivity, spirit and optimism that the world needs more of. Thank you for inspiring us all!

Photo credit (1 & 3) : @shitinthewoods

If I was to offer one piece of life advice it would be to identify your heros and figure out a way to make them your best friends. Roch Horton and Eve Davies have hearts bigger that anyone I’ve ever met, an insane commitment to creating life shaping experiences, and simply work harder than anyone alive. They are my dear friends and we are all better because of them. If you ran RUFA-Grandeur (@runningupforair) last weekend there is no doubt they made their mark on you. Am I right?

@ultratrailmatt and @wasatchwendy have pulled together an incredible RUFA on Kyhv Peak outside Provo, Utah. The route is incredible (7.4 miles round-trip / ~2,800’ ascent per lap), the view from the top is absolutely breathtaking, and the community is so inviting.  It is destined to be a classic in the series!! Put it on your list for next year.

Also, my mother has officially thrown down a DUFA (double RUFA). Possibly a TUFA with Malans coming up?
@runwithtara has created something incredibly special with @runningupforair Malans. Thanks for letting us be part of the day!!
Center of our world. Happy birthday (belated post) to the woman who does it all and makes our little family shine. Love you @mindy.campbell.pc
Fun on the west side this evening with an incredible crew.  #lifeelevated
March 11th 2023 gets my vote for most beautiful day of the year.

It was a complete honor to join the remarkable collection of humans that gathered for the Barkley this year. Shared a bunch of trail (and off trail!) time with some of the most resilient and optimistic people in the world and leave feeling elevated by the experience. It was a joy to spend portions of the route with Kyle Markesich, @karelsabbe, @thestring.bean, Jasmin Paris and others.  #bm100

To change the world, start with the very best people you can find. We threw a small party yesterday to celebrate the many successful 2023 RUFA (@runningupforair) events and scheme about the next chapter of our growing series. My sincere thank you to this group of remarkable humans for rallying around the cause and putting countless hours into creating life altering experiences. RUFA is special in the way it leverages our sport as a positive force in the push for cleaner air.

Peter Downing (@pwdowning - @sufferbetter ) and I have spent the last 6 years building a friendship centered around harnessing the sport of ultra running to do good for humanity. Amazingly, yesterday (3/25/2023) was the first time we had met in person! We took the opportunity to show him a proper Grandeur Peak OG-style summit!
March 26th, 2023. Skiing from the back deck!!
It’s always a great day when it starts with a quick lap up Kyhv Peak (route formerly known as Squawstruck). Thanks @stugleason !

Located west of Delta Utah, Notch Peak is home to one of the highest cliff faces in North America. The carbonate rock (limestone and dolomite) has remarkably fluctuating climbing style and rock quality.  Stu and I strung together a classic route, climbing up Western Hardman and Fin du Monde and rapping down Book of Saturday, exiting via the currently snow-filled gulley route.  The upper cirque is stunning and serious. We made a great team and executed the entire route near flawlessly. 

Do your homework before you climb on Notch Peak, and enjoy!!

I’ve been looking forward to this day for over 9 years! We climbed the West Slabs of Mount Olympus, scrambled up to the true (South) summit and down the standard trail.  We teamed up with our friends @brenn.crellin and his daughter Marlow. Phoebe and Marlow are little crushers, look out world!

Fun morning adventure during our yearly retreat to Island Park.  Mindy and I teamed up with the Crellins for a jaunt to the summit of Mt Jefferson, after which @brenn.crellin and I descended off the summit via its lovely scree-laden west side to connect with the CDT and onto Keg Springs.
What color do you paint your toenails?  Ruby recommends hot pink with glitter and two clear coats for durability.

Wow, what a route!  I love connecting Summit Park to Sundance and this year’s route was outstanding. Top 10 highlights:

1) Not seeing a single person up and over Summit Park Peak, in Toll Canyon, and on Murdock Peak. 
2) Bumping into @alexiscrellin who was out for a long run with her friend.
3) Helping a motorcyclist who had fallen off the trail on the northwest side of Mill Canyon Peak and slid down the hillside.  He was quite distraught and pleased that a couple of shorts-wearing runners took the time to help him. Kyle and I did some important bridge building here. 
4) Seeing the incredible waterfalls on the descent to Ant Knolls (you never see that during Wasatch 100!)
5) Climbing up a very snowy Mt Timpanogos and having a huge amount of glissading on the descent
6) Seeing a large gathering of baby goats
7) Chatting with the gentlemen who was going to leave a one-star review on the Timpooneke trail because it was supposed to be child friendly and he really struggled to push his baby stroller on it!
8) Enjoying class 5 bushwhack descending
9) Only taking 16 steps total on paved roads
10) Doing every step of this route with a remarkable human being, @kyle_markisich 

Details: 50+ miles and 15kft ascent; A true Wasatch classic!

The recent @footprintsrunning event at @patagoniaslc was so much fun. I have long been inspired by @thatdakotajones, aren’t we all?  Learning more about what he and @natebender10 are doing with Footprints Running was extremely motivating.  See link in my bio to learn more. 

I was honored to speak at the event, sharing the stage with @runningupforair ‘s new Program Director, Leslie Keener (@keenerview). It is a dream come true to have Leslie onboard and leading the next chapter of #RUFA. 

So much to be psyched about!!
Great run at @mooseonthelooserun by Phoebe!
Born to Run (and sing and dance). Ruby cruising into the finish line of @mooseonthelooserun.  Thanks to the remarkably talented @jana_herzog_ for capturing this photo.
Congrats @mindy.campbell.pc on finishing the super tough Tushar Mountain 70km race.  Phoebe, Ruby, and I are so proud of you.

This is Luc Hardink.  Luc is 12 years old and is a legend in the making. I first met him at #RUFA Grandeur in February 2023 where he easily threw down 3 laps in the 6 hour event. Yesterday he cruised into the finish line of the Tushar Mountain 70km (with 4,000m of ascent!) race looking cool, calm, and collected. I had a great chat with him at the finish and am amazed by him.  It will be so fun to see what he does in the near future!  #hero!!
Fun loop in the Stansbury Mountains on Saturday.
Absolutely perfect conditions at Ruth Lake (in the Uinta Mtns.) today!

Denis Cook.  This past weekend I had the pleasure of experiencing the community built around Denis Cook's rowdy 100 mile course in the Wyoming Range.  The event logistics were dialed, communication with participants top-notch, and maps for both runners and crews impeccable.  Aid stations and volunteers were some of the best I have ever seen.  All of this is remarkable for an event that is only 3 years old, a testament to Denis' detailed natured and applied observations from his many years of racing. 

What impresses me the most is just how much Denis cares and how genuine his motivations are. The effort that goes into putting on an event like this is monumental, no doubt 10x more than anyone who has not put on a race might think.  All of this is only possible with a volunteer community that rallies around a race director and their vision.

All of this effort is put in so a small group of people can push themselves in ways that provide perspective, that change their outlook, and make them better people.  This is something that Denis himself has likely experienced many times in his nearly 60 ultramarathons.  I am so impressed when the response to being a race consumer motivates one to turn around and provide a unique experience back to the community.  For this I thank you Denis, your family, and the entire volunteer team.
Post run soak!
Thimble Berries
River (Snake) and lake (Jackson) time with the McDermott family!

I have partnered with @womenofthewasatch and @lululemon to coordinate an incredible speaker series. It is call READY For The Trail Ahead and aims to build Resilience, share tools for Endurance and handle Adversity, and create a mindset of Determination for our Youth (READY). We all intuitively know these elements of growth are critical for our youngsters, however, options to build them are limited. This speaker series will showcase these elements through compelling stories from some of the most inspirational women in the sport of trail running. Our first session is right around the corner on September 7th (Thu) at the Park City Library and will feature the incredible Hillary Allen (@hillygoat_climbs). Sign up soon (link in bio) and bring to kids. Seating is limited. I hope to see you there! - Jared

🎟️ Ticket: Donation-based ($10 suggested)
📍 Location: Park City Library

I am thrilled to announce our second READY speaker session.  Jennifer Pharr Davis will be joining us on October 14th (Sat) near Park City Utah to share her lessons from the trail.  I have been a long-time fan of Jennifer for her many incredible endurance accomplishments.  However, it is the way she uses her unique story and observations of the world to inspire people that I am most impressed with.  As a parent, I consider it essential to expose my two daughters to real world heroes.  We have an incredible opportunity to do so on October 14th, don't miss it! (Link in bio)

There is a 2-hr run or a 1 hr social hike (perfect for kids and families) preceding the presentation from Jennifer.  Both are optional. There will also be a book signing after the presentation.  See you there!

Tickets are free, but donations are highly encouraged.  Seating is limited.  All funds collected will be donated to @girlsontherunutah and @girlandherbackpackslc.
I was outnumbered by Belgians on today’s run!  This doesn’t happen often in Salt Lake City.  Fun to show @karelsabbe and Kobe around the hills.
Following proper mountain runner host protocol, @kyle_markisich and I took @karelsabbe up the west side of Grandeur Peak.  He also got to experience a special .alt route for the descent.

Guardsman to Grandeur, an incredible 26 mile daddy-daughter linkup!  Best day ever?  This is one we’ll both remember.  The recently finished BST from the Pipeline to the west side of Grandeur is an incredible connector that will undoubtedly open the door to many fun linkups. #lovethybackyard #daddydaughter  #trailpizza

Join our next READY For The Trail Ahead speaker session on 11/17 (Friday). Our good friend and mountain athlete, Kelly Halpin (@kyehalpin), will join us to share stories from her many incredible adventures.  You won’t want to miss it!  Same venue as our last session.  Link in bio.

Yesterday, Phoebe and Ruby swam 146 and 81 times, respectively, across the pool (25m per length). They have had many swim meets over the years, but this was the most inspiring I’ve seen as it was a nonstop endurance challenge for 90 minutes. Neither of them complained at all!

After swimming, they still had energy so we went climbing until we reached complete shut down. Phoebe said “this is the first time in my life I have felt tired”.

Here is our 2023 Home Energy chart. Observations : 

- Total electrical energy consumption was 16.4MWh
- Total solar energy production was 13.9MWh
- 2023 was the first year where we were a fully EV family (two EVs).  One EV was occasionally charged at work and both were super-charged while on road-trips so this does not fully capture our driving energy for the year.
- Total home energy (excluding our EVs) was only 6.5MWh so I can easily claim the home to be net positive
- Total heating/cooling energy is very low at only 1.2MWh.  The extensive effort we put into our deep energy retrofit has paid off.  Note, we heat our home with a hybrid heat-pump system.  At extremely low temps, or when the outside unit is buried in the snow as happened in the winter of 22/23, it does shift over to the natural gas furnace.  As such this number is not a true total of heating/cooling energy.  I intend to more accurately measure natural gas consumption in 2024.
- All hot water (from an air-source heat pump tanked water heater) was only 690kWh, ~1.9kWh/day or < 0.5kWh/day/person.  
- Our ductless condensing heat-pump clothes dryer only used 149kWh for the entire year and enabled us to eliminate a large exhaust hole in our house.  It does take longer to dry, but the minimal energy usage is remarkable compared with a traditional resistive-style heater.
- All other measured loads (microwave, induction range, washing machine, refrig, oven, etc.) are all quite low, relatively speaking.
- We LOVE our EVs and they are the benchmark for efficiency in this day and age.  We drive a lot with extensive highway and canyon driving.  It's interesting to see how much the EVs now dwarf our very efficient house, which just goes to show how much energy most of use for transportation.  Combined, we pushed 9.6MWh into our two EVs at our house, nearly 69% of our total energy production!
- Hot-tubs are fun, but really dumb from an energy perspective.  We only ran ours for 1 month in 2023 and due to a failure haven't used it since.  It is an old  model and certainly not designed for efficiency.  This would be a fun area to innovate.

RUFA (@runningupforair) “pre-race” events are unlike any other.  Instead of talking about course markings and hydration drink flavors, we aim to educate and activate.  This year’s theme is Action! and we have structured the event to equip all participants and viewers (it will be streamed via YouTube) with an easy to understand list of things we can all do to make a difference.

We have assembled an incredible lineup of speakers, including a climate scientist, an expert in air quality legislation, and a lead from Utah Clean Energy who will share practical actions and overview the incentives that exist to accelerate the transition to clean energy. 

I am continually humbled and honored by the support of our presenting sponsor, @patagonia.  This year’s event will be hosted on 1/19 (Friday) at the Salt Lake City Patagonia store (@patagoniaslc). Our event will include a Happy Hour celebration from 5PM-7PM which will feature a DJ, mocktails, food truck, and other food tasting opportunities.  We will then screen the new RUFA documentary for the first time.  This will be followed by the aforementioned presentations and Q&A. 

Seating is limited and you need to RSVP.  See the link in my bio.
Park City, Utah
